WHEREAS the Ottawa Fire Service (OFS) tracks incidents involving lithium-ion battery fires, with 19 incidents recorded in 2024, 25 in 2025, and 10 reported to date in 2026, and over the past two years, as reported to the Ontario Fire Marshal, these fires accounted for approximately 1.5 per cent annually of all fires in the city;
WHEREAS the Ottawa Fire Service continues to monitor these trends to inform fire safety guidance and has the operational expertise to respond to incidents involving lithium-ion batteries, but does not have the authority to regulate their manufacture, distribution, or use within the community to the extent of senior levels of government;
WHEREAS the City of Ottawa currently has no specific municipal regulations governing the storage or charging of lithium-ion batteries used in devices such as e-scooters and similar micromobility devices, and municipalities would benefit from consistent, province-wide standards to ensure clarity, enforceability, and public safety;
WHEREAS the regulation of the manufacture, importation, and sale of lithium-ion batteries and related devices falls under the jurisdiction of the Government of Canada, while the Province of Ontario has jurisdiction over fire safety requirements, including indoor storage and charging, through the Ontario Fire Code, which does not currently contain specific provisions addressing the unique risks associated with lithium-ion batteries;
WHEREAS Ottawa City Council supports the review and development of clear, enforceable provisions within the Ontario Fire Code addressing the indoor storage and charging of lithium-ion batteries, specifically those used in micromobility devices (scooters, e-bikes etc);
THEREFORE BE IT RESOLVED THAT the Emergency Preparedness and Protective Services Committee recommend that City Council express its support for the inclusion of regulations on indoor storage and charging of lithium-ion batteries through the Ontario Fire Code;
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED THAT the City Clerk be directed to share a copy of this motion withthe Premier of Ontario, The Ontario Fire Marshal and the Ontario Minister of the Solicitor Generalon behalf of City Council.
